03933nam a22005175i 9780773569577DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20022002xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735695777 a10.1515/97807735695772doi  a(DE-B1597)656640  a(OCoLC)1394872819  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1090.5bD43 2002eb 7aBIO0060002bisacsh04a917.19/50421 aBarr, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrom Barrow to Boothia :bThe Arctic Journal of Chief Factor Peter Warren Dease, 1836-1839 /cWilliam Barr. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2002] 4cÂ©2002  a1 online resource (416 p.) :bIllustrations, maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRupert's Land Record Society Series ;v700tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tPreface -- tIllustrations and Maps -- tThe Men and Their Task -- tNorway House to Fort Chipewyan -- tThe Winter at Fort Chipewyan -- tDown the Slave and the Mackenzie -- tWest to Point Barrow and Back -- tThe First Wintering at Fort Confidence -- tEastwards, 1838 -- tThe Second Wintering at Fort Confidence -- tEastwards Again, 1839 -- tBack South to Fort Simpson -- tAftermath -- tAssessment -- tAppendix: Biographical Sketches -- tPublished Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver a three-year period from 1837 to 1939, operating from a base-camp at Fort Confidence on Great Bear Lake, the expedition achieved its goal. Despite serious problems with sea ice, Dease and Simpson, in some of the longest small-boat voyages in the history of the Arctic, mapped the remaining gaps in a model operation of efficient, economical, and safe exploration. Thomas Simpson's narrative, the standard source on the expedition, claimed the expedition's success for himself, stating "Dease is a worthy, indolent, illiterate soul, and moves just as I give the impulse." In From Barrow to Boothia William Barr shows that Dease's contribution was absolutely crucial to the expedition's success and makes Dease's sober, sensible, and modest account of the expedition available. Dease's journal, reproduced in full, is supplemented by a brief introduction to each section and detailed annotations that clarify and elaborate the text. By including relevant correspondence to and from expedition members, Barr captures the original words of the participants, offering insights into the character of both Dease and Simpson and making clear what really happened on this successful expedition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356957740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773569577423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773569577/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles